HOL-11: React Events

React events

React uses its own event system built on top of native browser events
Event handlers are passed as functions to JSX attributes like onClick
React normalizes events across different browsers for consistent behavior
Events in React are attached using camelCase names (onClick, not onclick)
Handlers are written as JavaScript functions, not strings, unlike traditional HTML

Event handlers

Functions that run in response to a specific event, like a button click
Can be defined as class methods or inline arrow functions within JSX
Often need to be bound to the component instance in class components (this binding)
Can accept and use the event object passed by React automatically
Used here to handle increment, decrement, welcome message, and click actions

Synthetic event

React wraps native browser events into a cross-browser wrapper called a SyntheticEvent
Ensures consistent event behavior regardless of which browser is being used
Has the same interface as native events, including methods like preventDefault()
Automatically passed as the first argument to event handler functions
Was used in this lab's "Click on me" button to demonstrate onClick handling

React event naming convention

Event names in JSX use camelCase, such as onClick, onChange, onSubmit
This differs from plain HTML, which uses all-lowercase event attributes
Handlers are passed as actual function references inside curly braces, not strings
Consistent naming makes it easy to recognize and predict event handler names
Following this convention is required for React to correctly attach the event listeners
